    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "It is absolutely possible that the balance is shifting based on unseen factors, and your intuition is correct; the flour and water are key players here. Different flours contain varying levels of natural microbes and different types of starches and proteins, which act as food for specific strains of bacteria or yeast. Furthermore, the mineral content in your water can influence the acidity, which in turn favors one type of microbe over another.\n\nSometimes, the starter goes through a phase where one dominant species temporarily overwhelms the others, leading to a period of sluggishness before the ecosystem rebalances itself. If you are using a whole-grain flour sometimes, that rush of complex nutrients can cause a massive, short-lived spike in activity, followed by a crash. To stabilize this, try using the same type of flour and water consistently for a few feeding cycles.",
